<DOC><DOCNO> AP900208-0288 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-90 2111EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Chevron-Refinery     02-08 0150</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Chevron-Refinery,0157</SECOND><HEAD>Unused Refinery, Shipping and Storage Operation To Be Sold toVenezuela</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chevron Corp. will sell an unused refineryand an operating shipping and storage facility in the Bahamas toVenezuela's state-owned oil company, Chevron announced Thursday.   No terms were disclosed for the mostly cash deal with Petroleosde Venezuela S.A., which owns the Citgo oil company. The deal mustbe approved by the governments of the Bahamas and Venezuela.   The 500,000-barrel-per-day refinery was shut in 1985, butstorage facilities for 20 million barrels and marine facilitiesthat can accommodate ships carrying up to 500,000 tons have beenused almost continuously since the entire facility was opened byChevron in 1970.   The operation in Freeport on Grand Bahama Island was run byChevron as the Bahamas Oil Refining Co.   Besides cash, Chevron will receive a long-term contract forfuture storage services at the facility.</TEXT></DOC>